profile_data: {"bio": "I have been passionate about mental health from a very young age. As a teen, I struggled to find and make meaningful connections and make sense of the world. I felt like no one could understand me, and I often felt not seen. I had difficulties coping and often wished I could escape and disappear, so I coped with many unhealthy means. As an immigrant, mental health and emotional well-being were taboo topics in my family and culture; I felt I had no one to talk to. After facing many changes, life transitions, and various traumas, I knew there had to be something I could do. I realized the way I was living my life wasn’t working any longer; it was not sustainable. I sought information to try to heal myself and understand the symptoms I was experiencing. Many books, classes, and some wonderful therapists later, I began to heal and make peace with the wounds that once brought me so much pain and chaos. I turned my personal quest for knowledge and healing into a career to help others do the same, and there is nothing that is more rewarding. In my free time, I love to take photos, write, make art, and take dance classes. I also enjoy spending time with my family and our dogs. I’ve learned to prioritize self-care and engage in more of what brings me joy. I love creating a healthy work-life balance and mirroring to my clients how to achieve the same, whether with school, social life, or something else. Life can be hard sometimes, and you do not have to do it alone! Fun fact: I am a foodie and will scope out all of the most epic restaurants to try no matter what city I am in. profile_data: {"bio": "Hello there! I am Ryan (he/him/his) and I am an Associate Marriage and Family Therapist in California. I received a Bachelor of Science in Psychology from the University of Washington, Seattle, and a master’s degree in counseling psychology from Santa Clara University. I have over four years of experience as a school-based therapist, and currently provide therapy to special education students with individualized education plans at the high school level. As a school-based therapist, I have worked primarily with students with emotional disturbance, developmental disabilities, depression, anxiety, ADHD, and autism. My own mental health challenges, such as family turmoil during adolescence and a relationship breakup during young adulthood, influenced me to pursue a career in the mental health field. In working through and learning from my challenges, I hope to support others in doing the same and achieve personal growth and change. profile_data: {"bio": "Welcome to Daybreak! profile_data: {"bio": "Hi, I'm Aliyah (she/her)! I'm an Associate Professional Clinical Counselor and I have a Master's degree in Child Development with a concentration on Early Childhood Mental Health from San Diego State University. I've always loved working with children in their families. Before I became a therapist, I was a preschool teacher. I have worked with children in an educational setting amongst a diverse population. In that setting, I have an experience that spans from teaching to developing and implementing behavior support plans. I have created and executed early childhood curriculum as well as assisted parents in developing behavior support plans that can be utilized at school and home. This has exposed me to different family dynamics, and the unique challenges each family may face. It has led me to learn about reflective supervision, restorative practices, trauma sensitivity, and what it means to be culturally competent. I pursued a career in the mental health field because of my what I've been exposed to growing up and the need to support the voices of the unheard. profile_data: {"bio": "Hi there!  My name is Lauren, and I am a Licensed Professional Clinical Counselor.  I grew up in Illinois before moving to sunny California, where I’ve lived for over 15 years. I’ve held previous roles as a School Counselor, ESL Teacher, and an Adoption/Foster Care Family Specialist where I gained a wealth of experience in supporting youth and families from diverse backgrounds and communities. I specialize in providing culturally sensitive and trauma-informed care for clients impacted by anxiety, depression, low self-esteem and body image issues, cultural challenges, relational issues, trauma, and more. My ultimate goal in therapy is to empower my clients to overcome challenges, embrace their strengths, and lead a fulfilling life aligned with their deepest values and aspirations. profile_data: {"bio": "I’m a Bay Area native with many years of experience in education and mental health services. My professional background and experiences, in addition to working as a mental health clinician (Associate Marriage & Family Therapist and Associate Professional Clinical Counselor), range from being a k- elementary school teacher, music teacher, educational consultant, and university department researcher. This also includes a tremendous amount of experience working with clients, students, and colleagues of many multicultural and background demographics. I hold a Bachelor of Science in Criminal Justice and a Master of Arts in Counseling Psychology.  My primary therapeutic approach is Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT). And Multicultural Therapeutic Orientation (MCO) as secondary. Although there are many therapeutic approaches in which I use, I believe these are good base approaches in all therapy to establish a therapeutic foundation. Within this scope of practice, I think that explorative methods can be included and used to understand the root difficulties that individuals may experience.   I also have experience in the treatment of the following through therapy: PTSD, Anxiety, Military Sexual Assault, Trauma, PTSD, Depression, Self-Image, Domestic Violence, Academic Stress and Anxiety, Agoraphobia, Social Anxiety, Military Veterans, ADHD, Teens, Adults, Social Inequity Trauma, Family Trauma, Adolescent Traumatic Stress, Career Stress, Substance Use and Addiction, and Grief and Loss.\"", "religion": "Prefer Not to Answer", "services": [], "ethnicity": "American Indian and Alaskan Native;Black or African American / African Descendant;Multiracial", "modalities": [], "npi_number": "1164270047", "self_gender": "Male", "specialties": [], "employment_type": "W2 Hourly", "sexual_orientation": "Heterosexual or straight"}

profile_data: {"bio": "Hi, I’m Carolyn! I’m a grounded, authentic person who values showing up as my true self. I know that finding a therapist you truly connect with can be tough, and I understand how important that journey is. My goal is to create a space where you can be fully yourself—no filters, no pretenses. Whether you need to vent, problem-solve, or explore solutions, I’m here to support you in navigating life’s challenges and working toward the goals that matter most to you.  I’ve had the privilege of working with diverse groups of people in settings like inpatient psychiatric hospitals, community mental health agencies, and substance use treatment centers. I’ve supported individuals with depression, anxiety, bipolar disorder, schizophrenia, and substance use disorders. I’m especially dedicated to providing affirming care to neurodiverse individuals and those who identify as disabled, ensuring they feel seen, heard, and respected.  A little about me: when I’m not working, I love creating art in various mediums, with a special connection to my cultural roots through traditional Native beadwork. I also enjoy exploring new places and spending time outdoors—whether it’s hiking, camping, or simply enjoying nature.", "religion": "Unaffiliated", "services": [], "ethnicity": "American Indian and Alaskan Native;White / European Descent", "modalities": [], "npi_number": "1366263550", "self_gender": "Female", "specialties": [], "employment_type": "W2 Hourly", "sexual_orientation": "Prefer Not to Answer"}

profile_data: {"bio": "During my undergraduate studies at California State University Fresno, I discovered a deep-seated passion for aiding individuals in managing their mental health and emotions. Earning my bachelor's degree strengthened my resolve to advocate for children whose voices are often overlooked. Growing up, I faced challenges in forming friendships and often wished for a therapist with whom I could share my feelings. Now, I find immense joy in supporting others who may feel as I did in my youth. My coping strategies are straightforward yet effective, such as walking my dog or spending quality time with my family. I also embrace more lighthearted approaches, like engaging in silly conversations with my dog or hosting family karaoke nights. profile_data: {"bio": "Hi there! I’m Skye Johnson, and I’m excited to share a bit about myself and the work I’m passionate about. I specialize in supporting individuals dealing with depression, anxiety, suicidal thoughts, self-harming behaviors, and relationship issues. These challenges can be tough, and my goal is to help you navigate through them with compassion and care. In our sessions, I use a variety of approaches to provide effective support. One method I use is Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT), which focuses on identifying and changing negative thought patterns and behaviors. CBT helps you develop practical skills to manage your symptoms and improve your overall well-being. I also incorporate Dialectical Behavior Therapy (DBT), which is effective for managing intense emotions and improving interpersonal relationships. DBT teaches skills for emotion regulation, distress tolerance, and effective communication. Reducing stigma around mental health, sexuality, and gender is crucial to my work. I aim to create a supportive environment where everyone feels comfortable discussing these topics openly and without judgment. Outside of work, I find joy in singing and spending time at the beach. Music helps me relax and connect with others, while the beach offers a peaceful escape and a chance to recharge. Thank you for learning about me. profile_data: {"bio": "Hello, and welcome to my bio.  I'm happy that you are here.    I am a Licensed Mental Health Counselor Associate (LCMHC-A) in the state of North Carolina.  I have earned a Master of Arts degree in Clinical Mental Health Counseling from Waynesburg University and a Master of Elementary Education degree from the University of Phoenix.   I am also a National Board-Certified Counselor.   I have over 20 years of experience working within the clinical mental health or education fields.  In the first 14 years of my career, I worked with youth, adolescents, young adults, and entire families providing in home, community, and school-based clinical counseling services to address behavioral, mental, developmental, and family related issues.  In the subsequent years, I have worked as an Elementary School Educator, an Outpatient Counselor & Residential In-Patient Clinician for dual- diagnosed women in treatment.  In most all the positions that I have served, I have supported individuals facing decades old trauma, substance abuse, mental & behavioral health issues, and problems related to grief and loss.  I have also served in many leadership roles throughout my career. I pride myself on being supportive, safe, and authentic while building therapeutic relationships with clients; and a common thread in all my work is “story.”  I love working with individuals to assist them in noticing not only “what happened,” but “how they are making sense of it.”   I ask questions like, “how is the story that you are telling yourself about your problematic life event serving or hindering you in your progress towards moving forward.”    Which then allows the individual to move towards a more solution-focused approach to healing, while also  equipping them with client specific coping skills to help them in managing triggers from current and past hurts.    Together we will explore how to weave the threads of life, even the painful, dark ones, together to create a sense of hope, purpose, and meaning.  Allow me to walk side by side with you to find healing and growth.", "religion": "Christian", "services": [], "ethnicity": "Black or African American / African Descendant", "modalities": [], "npi_number": "1194391763", "self_gender": "Female", "specialties": [], "employment_type": "W2 Hourly", "sexual_orientation": "Heterosexual or straight"}

In the first 14 years of my career, I worked with youth, adolescents, young adults, and entire families providing in home, community, and school-based clinical counseling services to address behavioral, mental, developmental, and family related issues.  In the subsequent years, I have worked as an Elementary School Educator, an Outpatient Counselor & Residential In-Patient Clinician for dual- diagnosed women in treatment.  In most all the positions that I have served, I have supported individuals facing decades old trauma, substance abuse, mental & behavioral health issues, and problems related to grief and loss.  I have also served in many leadership roles throughout my career. I pride myself on being supportive, safe, and authentic while building therapeutic relationships with clients; and a common thread in all my work is “story.”  I love working with individuals to assist them in noticing not only “what happened,” but “how they are making sense of it.”   I ask questions like, “how is the story that you are telling yourself about your problematic life event serving or hindering you in your progress towards moving forward.”    Which then allows the individual to move towards a more solution-focused approach to healing, while also  equipping them with client specific coping skills to help them in managing triggers from current and past hurts.
